  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "In `BuildAuthenticator`, configuration is read for `serviceaccounts` group resource ([here](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/cmd/kube-apiserver/app/server.go#L500)), but it gets used to access secrets as well ([here](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/cmd/kube-apiserver/app/server.go#L504)).\r\n\r\nRelevant code:\r\n```\r\n\t\t// we have to go direct to storage because the clientsets fail when they're initialized with some API versions excluded\r\n\t\t// we should stop trying to control them like that.\r\n\t\tstorageConfig, err := storageFactory.NewConfig(api.Resource(\"serviceaccounts\"))\r\n\t\tif err != nil {\r\n\t\t\treturn nil, nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unable to get serviceaccounts storage: %v\", err)\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t\tauthenticatorConfig.ServiceAccountTokenGetter = serviceaccountcontroller.NewGetterFromStorageInterface(storageConfig,\r\n                        storageFactory.ResourcePrefix(api.Resource(\"serviceaccounts\")), storageFactory.ResourcePrefix(api.Resource(\"secrets\")))\r\n```\r\n\r\nCauses issues while using encryption providers (reference: #46460) to encrypt secrets, since they get written using the transformer, but get read directly.\r\n\r\nWorkaround for now: Always include `serviceaccounts` along with `secrets` in the resources to be encrypted (in configuration file for encryption providers). Is bad from a consumer perspective.\r\n\r\nOther workarounds:\r\n* Put a special case in the transformer overrides. If consumer includes secrets in the configuration, also add serviceaccounts.\r\n* Find a way to merge the configurations for serviceaccounts and secrets in BuildAuthenticator. I am not familiar with BuildAuthenticator and thus would like some help evaluating how this would be feasible.\r\n\r\n@jcbsmpsn \r\n@deads2k (`git blame`)",
